{
  "version": 2,
  "name": "Garden",
  "description": "MESH_DEFORM_AND_CURVE_GEOMETRY_DESIGN P4 demo, re-wired single-pass per REALTIME_3D_DESIGN.md §10 D11+P8 — node.scatter_on_mesh + node.gltf_mesh_source's fit extension. A noise-pushed grid (node.grid_mesh -> node.push_mesh, height from node.simplex_field_2d -> node.make_triangles) is the terrain: object 0 of a single node.render_scene. node.scatter_on_mesh samples that SAME triangulated terrain, area-weighted, and writes an Array<InstanceTransform> field of placements (align_to_normal tilts each instance flush to the local slope), wired straight into object 1's instances_1 — a small lathed flower-form (node.range -> node.array_math MirrorRamp/ScaleOffset -> node.combine_xy profile -> node.revolve_curve -> node.make_triangles, a bundled procedural stand-in — the design does not bundle third-party scans) is object 1's mesh, drawn once per placement in the SAME shared-depth scene pass as the terrain, so a flower behind a ridge is correctly hidden instead of always compositing on top — the two-pass node.mix Max composite this replaced could not do that. Peter's real scanned-flowers .glb swaps in for the procedural flower chain via node.gltf_mesh_source's `path` + `fit=unit_box` (see the P4 worklog for the exact click-script) — everything downstream of the flower mesh (scatter, instancing) is unchanged.",
